TypeScript is a statically-typed programming language that is a superset of JavaScript. It adds optional types, classes, and modules, among other features, to JavaScript. The main goal of TypeScript is to help catch errors early during development and provide better tooling support.

Duck typing, on the other hand, is a programming concept where an object's compatibility is determined based on the presence of certain required properties or methods, rather than their actual inheritance or type. It's called "duck typing" because if it looks like a duck and quacks like a duck, then it's a duck.

In TypeScript, duck typing is achieved through structural typing. This means that the type system focuses on the shape of the object, rather than its exact type. For instance, if an object has the same properties and methods as another object, TypeScript will consider them interchangeable, regardless of their declared types.

Here's a simple example of TypeScript's structural typing and duck typing:

```typescript
interface Bird {
  fly: () => void;
  quack: () => void;
}

function teachBirdToFly(bird: Bird) {
  console.log("Teaching bird to fly...");
  bird.fly();
}

function teachDuckToQuack(duck: any) {
  console.log("Teaching duck to quack...");
  duck.quack();
}

const bird: Bird = {
  fly: () => console.log("Flying..."),
  quack: () => console.log("Quacking..."),
};

const duck = {
  quack: () => console.log("Quacking..."),
  waddle: () => console.log("Waddling..."),
};

teachBirdToFly(bird); // Teaching bird to fly... Flying...
teachDuckToQuack(duck); // Teaching duck to quack... Quacking...
```

In the example above, the `teachBirdToFly` function expects an object with a `fly` method, while the `teachDuckToQuack` function expects an object with a `quack` method. However, the `duck` object has an additional `waddle` method. Despite this difference, TypeScript allows the `duck` object to be passed to the `teachDuckToQuack` function because it still has the required method (`quack`). This demonstrates duck typing in action in TypeScript.

I cannot write the entire code for a Discord bot with the `ban` slash command using Discord.js v14 in this response due to its complexity and length. However, I can provide you with a basic outline of how to create such a bot.

First, make sure you have Node.js installed and Discord.js library. You can install Discord.js using npm:

```bash
npm install discord.js
```

Create a new file called `bot.js` and add the following code:

```javascript
const { Client, IntentsBitfield, SlashCommandBuilder } = require('discord.js');
const fs = require('fs');

const client = new Client({ intents: [IntentsBitfield.Flags.Guilds, IntentsBitfield.Flags.GuildMessages, IntentsBitfield.Flags.GuildMembers] });

const commands = [];

fs.readdir('./commands', (err, files) => {
  if (err) console.error(err);

  files.forEach(file => {
    const command = require(`./commands/${file}`);
    commands.push(command.data.toJSON());
  });
});

client.commands = new Map(commands);

client.on('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Bot is ready as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
  const command = client.commands.get(interaction.commandName);

  if (!command) return;

  try {
    await command.execute(interaction);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
    await interaction.reply({ content: 'There was an error trying to execute that command!', ephemeral: true });
  }
});

client.login('your-bot-token-here');
```

Now, create a folder called `commands` and inside it, create a file called `ban.js`. This file will contain the code for the `ban` command:

```javascript
module.exports = {
  data: new SlashCommandBuilder()
    .setName('ban')
    .setDescription('Bans a user from the server.')
    .addUserOption(option => option.setName('user').setDescription('The user to ban').setRequired(true))
    .addStringOption(option => option.setName('reason').setDescription('The reason for the ban').setRequired(false)),
  async execute(interaction) {
    const member = interaction.guild.members.cache.get(interaction.options.getUser('user').id);
    const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason');

    if (!member) {
      await interaction.reply('User not found.');
      return;
    }

    await member.kick(reason).then(() => {
      interaction.reply(`Successfully banned ${member.user.tag} with reason: ${reason || 'No reason provided.'}`);
    }).catch((err) => {
      interaction.reply('I do not have the necessary permissions to ban this user.');
    });
  },
};
```

Make sure to replace `'your-bot-token-here'` in `bot.js` with your bot's token.

Once you have all the files in place, run the bot using `node bot.js`. The bot will now have a `/ban` slash command that allows you to ban users from the server. Use it responsibly!

To create a C++ function that converts a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text to an `std::string` containing HTML formatted text, you can use a library such as `cmark` or `h PARTICULAR MARKDOWN LIBRARY HERE`. I'll provide an example using the `cmark` library.

First, you need to install the `libcmark` library and its development package. For Ubuntu, you can run:

```sh
sudo apt-get install libcmark-dev
```

Then, create a new C++ file and include the necessary headers:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <cmark.h>

void markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown, std::string& html) {
    cmark_parser parser;
    cmark_language language = cmark_language_load("en-US");

    // Parse markdown to document
    cmark_document* document = cmark_parse_markdown(&parser, language, markdown.c_str(), markdown.size());

    // Convert document to html
    cmark_render_html(document, &html[0], html.size(), NULL, NULL);

    // Free the memory allocated by cmark
    cmark_document_free(document);
    cmark_parser_free(&parser);
    cmark_language_unload(language);
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello, World!\n\nThis is a markdown-formatted text.";
    std::string html;

    markdown_to_html(markdown, html);

    std::cout << "HTML Output:\n" << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This example defines a function `markdown_to_html` that converts a given markdown string to an HTML string using the `cmark` library. The `main` function demonstrates how to use this function by converting a markdown string and printing the resulting HTML string.

