To solve the problem without using loops or recursion, we can use the bit manipulation technique. A number `n` is a power of three if and only if the binary representation of `n` has exactly one `1` bit and all the other bits are powers of three.

Here's the Java code:

```java
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n <= 0) return false; // check for negative numbers and zero

    int bit = 1; // initialize bit to 1
    int power = 1; // initialize power of three to 1

    while (n > power) { // keep shifting the power of three
        power *= 3;
        bit++;
    }

    return n == power || n == power / 3; // check if n is a power of three or a power of three divided by 3
}
```

The time complexity of this solution is O(log base 3 n) and the space complexity is O(1) as we don't use any extra space.

